  38 class _RouteClassAttributeToGetattr(object):
  39     """Route attribute access on a class to __getattr__.
  40 
  41     This is a descriptor, used to define attributes that act differently when
  42     accessed through an instance and through a class.  Instance access remains
  43     normal, but access to an attribute through a class will be routed to the
  44     class's __getattr__ method; this is done by raising AttributeError.
  45 
  46     """
  47     def __init__(self, fget=None):
  48         self.fget = fget
  49 
  50     def __get__(self, instance, ownerclass=None):
  51         if instance is None:
  52             raise AttributeError()
  53         return self.fget(instance)
  54 
  55     def __set__(self, instance, value):
  56         raise AttributeError("can't set attribute")
  57 
  58     def __delete__(self, instance):
  59         raise AttributeError("can't delete attribute")
  60

  62 def _is_descriptor(obj):
  63     """Returns True if obj is a descriptor, False otherwise."""
  64     return (
  65             hasattr(obj, '__get__') or
  66             hasattr(obj, '__set__') or
  67             hasattr(obj, '__delete__'))
  68 
  69 
  70 def _is_dunder(name):
  71     """Returns True if a __dunder__ name, False otherwise."""
  72     return (name[:2] == name[-2:] == '__' and
  73             name[2:3] != '_' and
  74             name[-3:-2] != '_' and
  75             len(name) > 4)
  76 
  77 
  78 def _is_sunder(name):
  79     """Returns True if a _sunder_ name, False otherwise."""
  80     return (name[0] == name[-1] == '_' and
  81             name[1:2] != '_' and
  82             name[-2:-1] != '_' and
  83             len(name) > 2)
  84

  86 def _make_class_unpicklable(cls):
  87     """Make the given class un-picklable."""
  88     def _break_on_call_reduce(self, protocol=None):
  89         raise TypeError('%r cannot be pickled' % self)
  90     cls.__reduce_ex__ = _break_on_call_reduce
  91     cls.__module__ = '<unknown>'

  94 class _EnumDict(dict):
  95     """Track enum member order and ensure member names are not reused.
  96 
  97     EnumMeta will use the names found in self._member_names as the
  98     enumeration member names.
  99 
 100     """
 101     def __init__(self):
 102         super(_EnumDict, self).__init__()
 103         self._member_names = []
 104 
 105     def __setitem__(self, key, value):
 106         """Changes anything not dundered or not a descriptor.
 107 
 108         If a descriptor is added with the same name as an enum member, the name
 109         is removed from _member_names (this may leave a hole in the numerical
 110         sequence of values).
 111 
 112         If an enum member name is used twice, an error is raised; duplicate
 113         values are not checked for.
 114 
 115         Single underscore (sunder) names are reserved.
 116 
 117         Note:   in 3.x __order__ is simply discarded as a not necessary piece
 118                 leftover from 2.x
 119 
 120         """
 121         if pyver >= 3.0 and key in ('_order_', '__order__'):
 122             return
 123         elif key == '__order__':
 124             key = '_order_'
 125         if _is_sunder(key):
 126             if key != '_order_':
 127                 raise ValueError('_names_ are reserved for future Enum use')
 128         elif _is_dunder(key):
 129             pass
 130         elif key in self._member_names:
 131             # descriptor overwriting an enum?
 132             raise TypeError('Attempted to reuse key: %r' % key)
 133         elif not _is_descriptor(value):
 134             if key in self:
 135                 # enum overwriting a descriptor?
 136                 raise TypeError('Key already defined as: %r' % self[key])
 137             self._member_names.append(key)
 138         super(_EnumDict, self).__setitem__(key, value)
 139

 141 # Dummy value for Enum as EnumMeta explicity checks for it, but of course until
 142 # EnumMeta finishes running the first time the Enum class doesn't exist.  This
 143 # is also why there are checks in EnumMeta like `if Enum is not None`
 144 Enum = None
 145

 147 class EnumMeta(type):
 148     """Metaclass for Enum"""
 149     @classmethod
 150     def __prepare__(metacls, cls, bases):
 151         return _EnumDict()
 152 
 153     def __new__(metacls, cls, bases, classdict):
 154         # an Enum class is final once enumeration items have been defined; it
 155         # cannot be mixed with other types (int, float, etc.) if it has an
 156         # inherited __new__ unless a new __new__ is defined (or the resulting
 157         # class will fail).
 158         if type(classdict) is dict:
 159             original_dict = classdict
 160             classdict = _EnumDict()
 161             for k, v in original_dict.items():
 162                 classdict[k] = v
 163 
 164         member_type, first_enum = metacls._get_mixins_(bases)
 165         __new__, save_new, use_args = metacls._find_new_(classdict, member_type,
 166                                                         first_enum)
 167         # save enum items into separate mapping so they don't get baked into
 168         # the new class
 169         members = dict((k, classdict[k]) for k in classdict._member_names)
 170         for name in classdict._member_names:
 171             del classdict[name]
 172 
 173         # py2 support for definition order
 174         _order_ = classdict.get('_order_')
 175         if _order_ is None:
 176             if pyver < 3.0:
 177                 try:
 178                     _order_ = [name for (name, value) in sorted(members.items(), key=lambda item: item[1])]
 179                 except TypeError:
 180                     _order_ = [name for name in sorted(members.keys())]
 181             else:
 182                 _order_ = classdict._member_names
 183         else:
 184             del classdict['_order_']
 185             if pyver < 3.0:
 186                 if isinstance(_order_, basestring):
 187                     _order_ = _order_.replace(',', ' ').split()
 188                 aliases = [name for name in members if name not in _order_]
 189                 _order_ += aliases
 190 
 191         # check for illegal enum names (any others?)
 192         invalid_names = set(members) & set(['mro'])
 193         if invalid_names:
 194             raise ValueError('Invalid enum member name(s): %s' % (
 195                 ', '.join(invalid_names), ))
 196 
 197         # save attributes from super classes so we know if we can take
 198         # the shortcut of storing members in the class dict
 199         base_attributes = set([a for b in bases for a in b.__dict__])
 200         # create our new Enum type
 201         enum_class = super(EnumMeta, metacls).__new__(metacls, cls, bases, classdict)
 202         enum_class._member_names_ = []               # names in random order
 203         if OrderedDict is not None:
 204             enum_class._member_map_ = OrderedDict()
 205         else:
 206             enum_class._member_map_ = {}             # name->value map
 207         enum_class._member_type_ = member_type
 208 
 209         # Reverse value->name map for hashable values.
 210         enum_class._value2member_map_ = {}
 211 
 212         # instantiate them, checking for duplicates as we go
 213         # we instantiate first instead of checking for duplicates first in case
 214         # a custom __new__ is doing something funky with the values -- such as
 215         # auto-numbering ;)
 216         if __new__ is None:
 217             __new__ = enum_class.__new__
 218         for member_name in _order_:
 219             value = members[member_name]
 220             if not isinstance(value, tuple):
 221                 args = (value, )
 222             else:
 223                 args = value
 224             if member_type is tuple:   # special case for tuple enums
 225                 args = (args, )     # wrap it one more time
 226             if not use_args or not args:
 227                 enum_member = __new__(enum_class)
 228                 if not hasattr(enum_member, '_value_'):
 229                     enum_member._value_ = value
 230             else:
 231                 enum_member = __new__(enum_class, *args)
 232                 if not hasattr(enum_member, '_value_'):
 233                     enum_member._value_ = member_type(*args)
 234             value = enum_member._value_
 235             enum_member._name_ = member_name
 236             enum_member.__objclass__ = enum_class
 237             enum_member.__init__(*args)
 238             # If another member with the same value was already defined, the
 239             # new member becomes an alias to the existing one.
 240             for name, canonical_member in enum_class._member_map_.items():
 241                 if canonical_member.value == enum_member._value_:
 242                     enum_member = canonical_member
 243                     break
 244             else:
 245                 # Aliases don't appear in member names (only in __members__).
 246                 enum_class._member_names_.append(member_name)
 247             # performance boost for any member that would not shadow
 248             # a DynamicClassAttribute (aka _RouteClassAttributeToGetattr)
 249             if member_name not in base_attributes:
 250                 setattr(enum_class, member_name, enum_member)
 251             # now add to _member_map_
 252             enum_class._member_map_[member_name] = enum_member
 253             try:
 254                 # This may fail if value is not hashable. We can't add the value
 255                 # to the map, and by-value lookups for this value will be
 256                 # linear.
 257                 enum_class._value2member_map_[value] = enum_member
 258             except TypeError:
 259                 pass
 260 
 261 
 262         # If a custom type is mixed into the Enum, and it does not know how
 263         # to pickle itself, pickle.dumps will succeed but pickle.loads will
 264         # fail.  Rather than have the error show up later and possibly far
 265         # from the source, sabotage the pickle protocol for this class so
 266         # that pickle.dumps also fails.
 267         #
 268         # However, if the new class implements its own __reduce_ex__, do not
 269         # sabotage -- it's on them to make sure it works correctly.  We use
 270         # __reduce_ex__ instead of any of the others as it is preferred by
 271         # pickle over __reduce__, and it handles all pickle protocols.
 272         unpicklable = False
 273         if '__reduce_ex__' not in classdict:
 274             if member_type is not object:
 275                 methods = ('__getnewargs_ex__', '__getnewargs__',
 276                         '__reduce_ex__', '__reduce__')
 277                 if not any(m in member_type.__dict__ for m in methods):
 278                     _make_class_unpicklable(enum_class)
 279                     unpicklable = True
 280 
 281 
 282         # double check that repr and friends are not the mixin's or various
 283         # things break (such as pickle)
 284         for name in ('__repr__', '__str__', '__format__', '__reduce_ex__'):
 285             class_method = getattr(enum_class, name)
 286             obj_method = getattr(member_type, name, None)
 287             enum_method = getattr(first_enum, name, None)
 288             if name not in classdict and class_method is not enum_method:
 289                 if name == '__reduce_ex__' and unpicklable:
 290                     continue
 291                 setattr(enum_class, name, enum_method)
 292 
 293         # method resolution and int's are not playing nice
 294         # Python's less than 2.6 use __cmp__
 295 
 296         if pyver < 2.6:
 297 
 298             if issubclass(enum_class, int):
 299                 setattr(enum_class, '__cmp__', getattr(int, '__cmp__'))
 300 
 301         elif pyver < 3.0:
 302 
 303             if issubclass(enum_class, int):
 304                 for method in (
 305                         '__le__',
 306                         '__lt__',
 307                         '__gt__',
 308                         '__ge__',
 309                         '__eq__',
 310                         '__ne__',
 311                         '__hash__',
 312                         ):
 313                     setattr(enum_class, method, getattr(int, method))
 314 
 315         # replace any other __new__ with our own (as long as Enum is not None,
 316         # anyway) -- again, this is to support pickle
 317         if Enum is not None:
 318             # if the user defined their own __new__, save it before it gets
 319             # clobbered in case they subclass later
 320             if save_new:
 321                 setattr(enum_class, '__member_new__', enum_class.__dict__['__new__'])
 322             setattr(enum_class, '__new__', Enum.__dict__['__new__'])
 323         return enum_class
 324 
 325     def __bool__(cls):
 326         """
 327         classes/types should always be True.
 328         """
 329         return True
 330 
 331     def __call__(cls, value, names=None, module=None, type=None, start=1):
 332         """Either returns an existing member, or creates a new enum class.
 333 
 334         This method is used both when an enum class is given a value to match
 335         to an enumeration member (i.e. Color(3)) and for the functional API
 336         (i.e. Color = Enum('Color', names='red green blue')).
 337 
 338         When used for the functional API: `module`, if set, will be stored in
 339         the new class' __module__ attribute; `type`, if set, will be mixed in
 340         as the first base class.
 341 
 342         Note: if `module` is not set this routine will attempt to discover the
 343         calling module by walking the frame stack; if this is unsuccessful
 344         the resulting class will not be pickleable.
 345 
 346         """
 347         if names is None:  # simple value lookup
 348             return cls.__new__(cls, value)
 349         # otherwise, functional API: we're creating a new Enum type
 350         return cls._create_(value, names, module=module, type=type, start=start)
 351 
 352     def __contains__(cls, member):
 353         return isinstance(member, cls) and member.name in cls._member_map_
 354 
 355     def __delattr__(cls, attr):
 356         # nicer error message when someone tries to delete an attribute
 357         # (see issue19025).
 358         if attr in cls._member_map_:
 359             raise AttributeError(
 360                     "%s: cannot delete Enum member." % cls.__name__)
 361         super(EnumMeta, cls).__delattr__(attr)
 362 
 363     def __dir__(self):
 364         return (['__class__', '__doc__', '__members__', '__module__'] +
 365                 self._member_names_)
 366 
 367     @property
 368     def __members__(cls):
 369         """Returns a mapping of member name->value.
 370 
 371         This mapping lists all enum members, including aliases. Note that this
 372         is a copy of the internal mapping.
 373 
 374         """
 375         return cls._member_map_.copy()
 376 
 377     def __getattr__(cls, name):
 378         """Return the enum member matching `name`
 379 
 380         We use __getattr__ instead of descriptors or inserting into the enum
 381         class' __dict__ in order to support `name` and `value` being both
 382         properties for enum members (which live in the class' __dict__) and
 383         enum members themselves.
 384 
 385         """
 386         if _is_dunder(name):
 387             raise AttributeError(name)
 388         try:
 389             return cls._member_map_[name]
 390         except KeyError:
 391             raise AttributeError(name)
 392 
 393     def __getitem__(cls, name):
 394         return cls._member_map_[name]
 395 
 396     def __iter__(cls):
 397         return (cls._member_map_[name] for name in cls._member_names_)
 398 
 399     def __reversed__(cls):
 400         return (cls._member_map_[name] for name in reversed(cls._member_names_))
 401 
 402     def __len__(cls):
 403         return len(cls._member_names_)
 404 
 405     __nonzero__ = __bool__
 406 
 407     def __repr__(cls):
 408         return "<enum %r>" % cls.__name__
 409 
 410     def __setattr__(cls, name, value):
 411         """Block attempts to reassign Enum members.
 412 
 413         A simple assignment to the class namespace only changes one of the
 414         several possible ways to get an Enum member from the Enum class,
 415         resulting in an inconsistent Enumeration.
 416 
 417         """
 418         member_map = cls.__dict__.get('_member_map_', {})
 419         if name in member_map:
 420             raise AttributeError('Cannot reassign members.')
 421         super(EnumMeta, cls).__setattr__(name, value)
 422 
 423     def _create_(cls, class_name, names=None, module=None, type=None, start=1):
 424         """Convenience method to create a new Enum class.
 425 
 426         `names` can be:
 427 
 428         * A string containing member names, separated either with spaces or
 429           commas.  Values are auto-numbered from 1.
 430         * An iterable of member names.  Values are auto-numbered from 1.
 431         * An iterable of (member name, value) pairs.
 432         * A mapping of member name -> value.
 433 
 434         """
 435         if pyver < 3.0:
 436             # if class_name is unicode, attempt a conversion to ASCII
 437             if isinstance(class_name, unicode):
 438                 try:
 439                     class_name = class_name.encode('ascii')
 440                 except UnicodeEncodeError:
 441                     raise TypeError('%r is not representable in ASCII' % class_name)
 442         metacls = cls.__class__
 443         if type is None:
 444             bases = (cls, )
 445         else:
 446             bases = (type, cls)
 447         classdict = metacls.__prepare__(class_name, bases)
 448         _order_ = []
 449 
 450         # special processing needed for names?
 451         if isinstance(names, basestring):
 452             names = names.replace(',', ' ').split()
 453         if isinstance(names, (tuple, list)) and isinstance(names[0], basestring):
 454             names = [(e, i+start) for (i, e) in enumerate(names)]
 455 
 456         # Here, names is either an iterable of (name, value) or a mapping.
 457         item = None  # in case names is empty
 458         for item in names:
 459             if isinstance(item, basestring):
 460                 member_name, member_value = item, names[item]
 461             else:
 462                 member_name, member_value = item
 463             classdict[member_name] = member_value
 464             _order_.append(member_name)
 465         # only set _order_ in classdict if name/value was not from a mapping
 466         if not isinstance(item, basestring):
 467             classdict['_order_'] = _order_
 468         enum_class = metacls.__new__(metacls, class_name, bases, classdict)
 469 
 470         # TODO: replace the frame hack if a blessed way to know the calling
 471         # module is ever developed
 472         if module is None:
 473             try:
 474                 module = _sys._getframe(2).f_globals['__name__']
 475             except (AttributeError, ValueError):
 476                 pass
 477         if module is None:
 478             _make_class_unpicklable(enum_class)
 479         else:
 480             enum_class.__module__ = module
 481 
 482         return enum_class
 483 
 484     @staticmethod
 485     def _get_mixins_(bases):
 486         """Returns the type for creating enum members, and the first inherited
 487         enum class.
 488 
 489         bases: the tuple of bases that was given to __new__
 490 
 491         """
 492         if not bases or Enum is None:
 493             return object, Enum
 494 
 495 
 496         # double check that we are not subclassing a class with existing
 497         # enumeration members; while we're at it, see if any other data
 498         # type has been mixed in so we can use the correct __new__
 499         member_type = first_enum = None
 500         for base in bases:
 501             if  (base is not Enum and
 502                     issubclass(base, Enum) and
 503                     base._member_names_):
 504                 raise TypeError("Cannot extend enumerations")
 505         # base is now the last base in bases
 506         if not issubclass(base, Enum):
 507             raise TypeError("new enumerations must be created as "
 508                     "`ClassName([mixin_type,] enum_type)`")
 509 
 510         # get correct mix-in type (either mix-in type of Enum subclass, or
 511         # first base if last base is Enum)
 512         if not issubclass(bases[0], Enum):
 513             member_type = bases[0]     # first data type
 514             first_enum = bases[-1]  # enum type
 515         else:
 516             for base in bases[0].__mro__:
 517                 # most common: (IntEnum, int, Enum, object)
 518                 # possible:    (<Enum 'AutoIntEnum'>, <Enum 'IntEnum'>,
 519                 #               <class 'int'>, <Enum 'Enum'>,
 520                 #               <class 'object'>)
 521                 if issubclass(base, Enum):
 522                     if first_enum is None:
 523                         first_enum = base
 524                 else:
 525                     if member_type is None:
 526                         member_type = base
 527 
 528         return member_type, first_enum
 529 
 530     if pyver < 3.0:
 531         @staticmethod
 532         def _find_new_(classdict, member_type, first_enum):
 533             """Returns the __new__ to be used for creating the enum members.
 534 
 535             classdict: the class dictionary given to __new__
 536             member_type: the data type whose __new__ will be used by default
 537             first_enum: enumeration to check for an overriding __new__
 538 
 539             """
 540             # now find the correct __new__, checking to see of one was defined
 541             # by the user; also check earlier enum classes in case a __new__ was
 542             # saved as __member_new__
 543             __new__ = classdict.get('__new__', None)
 544             if __new__:
 545                 return None, True, True      # __new__, save_new, use_args
 546 
 547             N__new__ = getattr(None, '__new__')
 548             O__new__ = getattr(object, '__new__')
 549             if Enum is None:
 550                 E__new__ = N__new__
 551             else:
 552                 E__new__ = Enum.__dict__['__new__']
 553             # check all possibles for __member_new__ before falling back to
 554             # __new__
 555             for method in ('__member_new__', '__new__'):
 556                 for possible in (member_type, first_enum):
 557                     try:
 558                         target = possible.__dict__[method]
 559                     except (AttributeError, KeyError):
 560                         target = getattr(possible, method, None)
 561                     if target not in [
 562                             None,
 563                             N__new__,
 564                             O__new__,
 565                             E__new__,
 566                             ]:
 567                         if method == '__member_new__':
 568                             classdict['__new__'] = target
 569                             return None, False, True
 570                         if isinstance(target, staticmethod):
 571                             target = target.__get__(member_type)
 572                         __new__ = target
 573                         break
 574                 if __new__ is not None:
 575                     break
 576             else:
 577                 __new__ = object.__new__
 578 
 579             # if a non-object.__new__ is used then whatever value/tuple was
 580             # assigned to the enum member name will be passed to __new__ and to the
 581             # new enum member's __init__
 582             if __new__ is object.__new__:
 583                 use_args = False
 584             else:
 585                 use_args = True
 586 
 587             return __new__, False, use_args
 588     else:
 589         @staticmethod
 590         def _find_new_(classdict, member_type, first_enum):
 591             """Returns the __new__ to be used for creating the enum members.
 592 
 593             classdict: the class dictionary given to __new__
 594             member_type: the data type whose __new__ will be used by default
 595             first_enum: enumeration to check for an overriding __new__
 596 
 597             """
 598             # now find the correct __new__, checking to see of one was defined
 599             # by the user; also check earlier enum classes in case a __new__ was
 600             # saved as __member_new__
 601             __new__ = classdict.get('__new__', None)
 602 
 603             # should __new__ be saved as __member_new__ later?
 604             save_new = __new__ is not None
 605 
 606             if __new__ is None:
 607                 # check all possibles for __member_new__ before falling back to
 608                 # __new__
 609                 for method in ('__member_new__', '__new__'):
 610                     for possible in (member_type, first_enum):
 611                         target = getattr(possible, method, None)
 612                         if target not in (
 613                                 None,
 614                                 None.__new__,
 615                                 object.__new__,
 616                                 Enum.__new__,
 617                                 ):
 618                             __new__ = target
 619                             break
 620                     if __new__ is not None:
 621                         break
 622                 else:
 623                     __new__ = object.__new__
 624 
 625             # if a non-object.__new__ is used then whatever value/tuple was
 626             # assigned to the enum member name will be passed to __new__ and to the
 627             # new enum member's __init__
 628             if __new__ is object.__new__:
 629                 use_args = False
 630             else:
 631                 use_args = True
 632 
 633             return __new__, save_new, use_args

 642 temp_enum_dict = {}
 643 temp_enum_dict['__doc__'] = "Generic enumeration.\n\n    Derive from this class to define new enumerations.\n\n"
 644 
 645 def __new__(cls, value):
 646     # all enum instances are actually created during class construction
 647     # without calling this method; this method is called by the metaclass'
 648     # __call__ (i.e. Color(3) ), and by pickle
 649     if type(value) is cls:
 650         # For lookups like Color(Color.red)
 651         value = value.value
 652         #return value
 653     # by-value search for a matching enum member
 654     # see if it's in the reverse mapping (for hashable values)
 655     try:
 656         if value in cls._value2member_map_:
 657             return cls._value2member_map_[value]
 658     except TypeError:
 659         # not there, now do long search -- O(n) behavior
 660         for member in cls._member_map_.values():
 661             if member.value == value:
 662                 return member
 663     raise ValueError("%s is not a valid %s" % (value, cls.__name__))
 664 temp_enum_dict['__new__'] = __new__
 665 del __new__
 666 
 667 def __repr__(self):
 668     return "<%s.%s: %r>" % (
 669             self.__class__.__name__, self._name_, self._value_)
 670 temp_enum_dict['__repr__'] = __repr__
 671 del __repr__
 672 
 673 def __str__(self):
 674     return "%s.%s" % (self.__class__.__name__, self._name_)
 675 temp_enum_dict['__str__'] = __str__
 676 del __str__
 677 
 678 if pyver >= 3.0:
 679     def __dir__(self):
 680         added_behavior = [
 681                 m
 682                 for cls in self.__class__.mro()
 683                 for m in cls.__dict__
 684                 if m[0] != '_' and m not in self._member_map_
 685                 ]
 686         return (['__class__', '__doc__', '__module__', ] + added_behavior)
 687     temp_enum_dict['__dir__'] = __dir__
 688     del __dir__

 690 def __format__(self, format_spec):
 691     # mixed-in Enums should use the mixed-in type's __format__, otherwise
 692     # we can get strange results with the Enum name showing up instead of
 693     # the value
 694 
 695     # pure Enum branch
 696     if self._member_type_ is object:
 697         cls = str
 698         val = str(self)
 699     # mix-in branch
 700     else:
 701         cls = self._member_type_
 702         val = self.value
 703     return cls.__format__(val, format_spec)
 704 temp_enum_dict['__format__'] = __format__
 705 del __format__

 713     def __cmp__(self, other):
 714         if type(other) is self.__class__:
 715             if self is other:
 716                 return 0
 717             return -1
 718         return NotImplemented
 719         raise TypeError("unorderable types: %s() and %s()" % (self.__class__.__name__, other.__class__.__name__))
 720     temp_enum_dict['__cmp__'] = __cmp__
 721     del __cmp__

 765 def __reduce_ex__(self, proto):
 766     return self.__class__, (self._value_, )
 767 temp_enum_dict['__reduce_ex__'] = __reduce_ex__
 768 del __reduce_ex__

 770 # _RouteClassAttributeToGetattr is used to provide access to the `name`
 771 # and `value` properties of enum members while keeping some measure of
 772 # protection from modification, while still allowing for an enumeration
 773 # to have members named `name` and `value`.  This works because enumeration
 774 # members are not set directly on the enum class -- __getattr__ is
 775 # used to look them up.
 776 
 777 @_RouteClassAttributeToGetattr
 778 def name(self):
 779     return self._name_
 780 temp_enum_dict['name'] = name
 781 del name
 782 
 783 @_RouteClassAttributeToGetattr
 784 def value(self):
 785     return self._value_
 786 temp_enum_dict['value'] = value
 787 del value
 788 
 789 @classmethod
 790 def _convert(cls, name, module, filter, source=None):
 791     """
 792     Create a new Enum subclass that replaces a collection of global constants
 793     """
 794     # convert all constants from source (or module) that pass filter() to
 795     # a new Enum called name, and export the enum and its members back to
 796     # module;
 797     # also, replace the __reduce_ex__ method so unpickling works in
 798     # previous Python versions
 799     module_globals = vars(_sys.modules[module])
 800     if source:
 801         source = vars(source)
 802     else:
 803         source = module_globals
 804     members = dict((name, value) for name, value in source.items() if filter(name))
 805     cls = cls(name, members, module=module)
 806     cls.__reduce_ex__ = _reduce_ex_by_name
 807     module_globals.update(cls.__members__)
 808     module_globals[name] = cls
 809     return cls
 810 temp_enum_dict['_convert'] = _convert
 811 del _convert
 812 
 813 Enum = EnumMeta('Enum', (object, ), temp_enum_dict)
 814 del temp_enum_dict

 819 class IntEnum(int, Enum):
 820     """Enum where members are also (and must be) ints"""
 821 
 822 def _reduce_ex_by_name(self, proto):
 823     return self.name

 825 def unique(enumeration):
 826     """Class decorator that ensures only unique members exist in an enumeration."""
 827     duplicates = []
 828     for name, member in enumeration.__members__.items():
 829         if name != member.name:
 830             duplicates.append((name, member.name))
 831     if duplicates:
 832         duplicate_names = ', '.join(
 833                 ["%s -> %s" % (alias, name) for (alias, name) in duplicates]
 834                 )
 835         raise ValueError('duplicate names found in %r: %s' %
 836                 (enumeration, duplicate_names)
 837                 )
 838     return enumeration
